		<!--exercise>
			<title>16 Compound Statements using <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m></title>
			<idx><h>16 Compound Statements using <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m></h></idx>
			<statement>
				<p>

The table below shows that are 16 possible outcomes for a compound statement involving <m>P</m> and/or <m>Q</m>. Find a statement corresponding to each of these 16 possibilities! Most of your statements will depend on both <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>, but some will only depend on one or the other.

			</p><p>
You will need one final connector: the exclusive or <m>P \oplus Q</m> which is true when <em>exactly one</em> of <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m> is <em> true</em>.

<me>
\begin{array}{c|c||c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c}
P &amp; Q &amp;  &amp;  &amp;  &amp;  &amp;  &amp;  &amp;  &amp;
&amp;  &amp;  &amp;  &amp;  &amp;  &amp;  &amp;
&amp;  \\
\hline
T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F\\
T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F\\
F&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F&amp;T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F&amp;T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F&amp;T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F\\
F&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F
\end{array}
</me>

<xsolution>
<p>

I'll split this into two tables for readability. We have
<me>
\begin{array}{c|c||c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c}
P &amp; Q &amp; P \vee \neg P &amp; P \vee Q  &amp; P \vee \neg Q  &amp; P &amp;  \neg P \vee Q &amp; Q  &amp;  P \Leftrightarrow Q  &amp; P \wedge \neg Q \\
\hline
T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T\\
T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F\\
F&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F&amp;T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F\\
F&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F
\end{array}
</me>
and
<me>
\begin{array}{c|c||c|c|c|c|c|c|c|c}
P &amp; Q &amp; P \wedge \neg P &amp; P \oplus Q  &amp; \neg Q  &amp; P \wedge \neg Q  &amp; \neg P  &amp; \neg P \wedge  Q  &amp; \neg P \wedge \neg Q  &amp; P \wedge \neg P \\
\hline
T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F\\
T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F&amp;F\\
F&amp;T&amp;T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F&amp;T&amp;T&amp;F&amp;F\\
F&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F&amp;T&amp;F
\end{array}
</me>

Hopefully, you noticed that there is an "anti-symmetry" to this table. The first column is the negation of the last column. The second column is the negation of the second-to-last column, and so on! So you can negate the  <m>k</m>th statement <m>k</m> to find the <m>(17-k)</m>th statement.

</p>
</xsolution>

